data.content:
Three breaking changes affect your code. Here's what breaks and how to fix each:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes `Func`, not `Expression`

Your expression-tree code **won't compile**. The new overload accepts a plain lambda, so conditional setters become trivial:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

Delete all the `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` machinery.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — now auto-uniquified & full-path nested

**Two related changes:**

- **Duplicate names**: `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously silently shared one column. EF 10 appends a number (e.g. `Street1`) to disambiguate.
- **Nested types**: `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was `BillingAddress_City`; now becomes `Payment_BillingAddress_City`.

If you have an existing database and need the **old** column names, pin them explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});

// For nested complex types, pin the old shorter name:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

If starting fresh, the new defaults are safer — just regenerate your migration.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gained a `string logCommandText` parameter for redacted SQL logging. Add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (sensitive data redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual execution SQL
    }
}
```

Apply the same `string logCommandText` addition to `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, `CommandScalarExecuted`, `CommandNonQueryExecuting`, `CommandNonQueryExecuted`, etc.
